[In a recent posting (20141006.2828583) we reported that, according to OIE data, no Q fever vaccination is applied in Germany. It appears that the information from Germany in WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database Interface) is incomplete (reports for the period January 2005-June 2013 visited; later reports, for terrestrial animals, not yet available). Is there no federal database, collecting information about the status of Q fever vaccination in animals throughout Germany?

As indicated at the official notification above, vaccination with the approved vaccine "Coxevac" has become compulsory for all ruminants in the zone established in Bad-Duerkheim; a map is included at the source URL above.

The situation in the various "laender" (states) of the German federation, in relation to Q fever vaccination, deserves to be clarified. Is there a uniform prevention (including vaccination) and control policy?

Details on the vaccine mentioned are available at http://www.ema.europa.eu/docs/en_GB/document_library/EPAR_-_Product_Information/veterinary/000155/WC500097773.pdf (thanks to Sabine Zentis for this source). The manufacturer provides instructions for its application in cattle and goats; the vaccine has not been licensed for sheep. To overcome this, the authorities in Bad-Duerkheim included, in their official notification, the following comment: "for the vaccination of sheep, the manufacturer's instructions for the vaccination of goats should be followed". - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2839528,9631.]
